Behold! The first completely new from-scratch model by yours truly! This particular aircraft...isn't an aircraft at all. It does not exist in the real world. 
As I was walking towards the bus to take me to the airport for class, I conceived the idea of designing an aircraft using the same modeling technique I've refined to this point, but on a completely new design, with no basis on any existing aircraft in production. I spent about an hour brainstorming on pen and paper, before settling on a concept that I thought would be interesting to model. I looked to the Icon A5, and the Cirrus Vision for inspiration. 
This model is built from scratch, with the wings, landing gear, horizontal stabilizers and antennae highly modified from my stock of models. This "kit-jet" can make an excellent demonstration of both the capabilities of Google Sketchup, and the potential for incredible creativity. If you choose to print this, please let me know your results so I can make improvements. Enjoy!

title: Spectrophotometer Retention Device (for X-Rite Chroma4 and Chroma5 meters)

description.text:
I work in the medical field, where our monitors have to be calibrated regularly. For the majority of them, we have to hold a spectrophotometer against the screen for 10-15 minutes each. As long as I've been doing this, I've been using 2 large, thick elastic bands tied together and hooked onto opposing corners of the monitor to hold this "puck". Being a new 3D printer owner, I decided to try modelling a part to do this for me without the hassle of trying to get elastic bands to stay on monitors with rounded edges. :) Please note, I have NOT YET PRINTED THIS THING. I plan to do so over the next few days, but wanted to publish it in case anyone had a critique or suggestion for me. REVISION 1 - Feb 17, 2016

  • I printed out a set of the legs, and they were too loose - I enlarged the ends of the smallest part of the legs (the T shapes) to be just .2mm smaller than the socket that receives it.

  • I shortened the overall size of the device by about 2 inches, as it was just TOO big to be practical on the 22" monitors we use them on (the shortest length possible was about 8 inches from top of monitor to center of meter)
    • I still have yet to print this device in its entirety, so until I do, I'm leaving this listed as a "Thing in progress"

Other items needed For the sliding arm, you'll need 1 M3 hex nut (approx 5.2mm across the flats) and an M3 thumb screw or similar easy-to-turn screw. Update Added two printable thumbscrews, since you cant seem to buy just one anywhere....at least not cheaply.
Brute Force method :) I sat here with one of each spectrophotometer and a pair of Neiko digital calipers, and measured it - designed it all pretty much on the fly.

author: Kezat

title: Ultimate Modular 3D Printer Tool Holder Rack

description.text:
This modular tool holder / rack is specifically designed with a 3D Printer in mind and the tools used for everyday printing needs. The modular holders slide on a rail system and can be swapped out and rearranged at any time. Duplicates can be printed and added to the rack. Multiple rail lengths are included for a variety of combinations. All modular holders are 36mm wide, except one. The Pen Holder is 45 mm wide. The end caps are 10mm wide. End caps are meant to be tapped in with a mallet (no glue necessary). Some holders print in multiple pieces to eliminate the need for support while printing, SImply super glue the pieces together after printing. Note: My printer tolerances turned out to be 0.3mm. This is the gap needed for the holders to slide freely in the rail system without too much friction. Hopefully this gap is common for other printers. My prints glide smoothly. The odd rail lengths are due to giving an extra 25mm or so of free space. I found out giving a little extra space is a good idea to slide tools as needed. The following tools have been accommodated in the rack.
  • Digital Caliper

PROBLEM! Your totally sweet bike does not currently emit enough light to allow you to ride in the dark without endangering yourself and/or your aformentioned totally sweet ride. What to do? Well, there are a number of options open to you: you could hoard radium and staple it to your pedals, but that might cause things to glow in situations where it's not appropriate (for instance, secret missions). Glow sticks can be tough to find in a pinch, and taste horrible. Purpose-built bicycle headlamps can cost an arm and a leg and aren't really useful outside of bicycle-bound illumination. In an effort to redress all of this, I've created an adapter that allows you to attach a small flashlight to the handlebars of your very own bicycle. Get a good standalone flashlight, and attach it to your bike only when you need a light! I use a 4sevens Quark Mini 123, but practically any small flashlight should fit. This thing prints just fine without support, even if the geometry looks a little weird.

1) Print.
2) Find a couple of strips of hook-and-loop fastener and put one through each slot on the block.
3) Strap your flashlight to the block, and the block to your handlebars.
4) Ride!

author: tuduong

title: Glare shields for internal lights on OpenROV 2.8

description.text:
These two parts form internal glare shields to improve the dark water performance of the stock LED's on the OpenROV 2.8 light board.The outer profile matches the O.D. of the end plates on the electronics frame, which gives a pretty small clearance with the I.D. of the acrylic tube. I might make them just a little larger, or experiment with some black foam gaskets, but so far, they seem to help a lot and I'm reluctant to scratch the inside of the acrylic tube. I will definitely also try some black felt on the front of the light board around the circular cutouts you can clearly see reflected in the second photo. They mount via the little screws that secure the light board to the camera board.
The photos are of a very dark hallway, with the internal lights at full bright. The second photo is with the glare shields installed. The first is without.

Even though there are lots of great gears on thingiverse, I couldn't resist the urge to model some too :) The combinations of parameters are too many to upload an STL for each, so I just picked a few. I also made a version for helical gears: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1339

The openSCAD file accepts parameters for height, pitch diameter, shaft diameter, teeth (number of teeth, addendum, dedendum, tooth width), shape (solid, star, circles), extrude in and out (diameter, height), rome (pitch diameter, gear height, number of teeth, addendum, dedendum, tooth width, rotation). There is also an option to involute based on pressure angle, but it's not the real thing - I'm waiting for the rest of the http://openscad.org documentation to apply the proper geometry formula here.

description.text:
Deadpool logo which can be attached to your belt! How awesome!! Yay! ^_^ Made in honor to our beloved killing machine, this is a logo which resembles the one in the movie costume on his belt.
With the difference that it is not the buckle itself, but you can attach it to your belt through the hole at the back of the logo.
The belt can have maximum 3 cm width, and sould not be too thick. But of course the model can be resized.

Printer:

No

Notes: Nozzle: 0.5mm

Printing the parts separately and assembling them Print out the three colors separately: red, black, silver (this can be white if you like) Watch out for the big bridge in the red part!
There will be strings bent down, unless you have a printer with 2 heads and soluble support material. For most of us this is not available, so be aware of the mess under that bridge, and clean it up.
Print this part out first, and test your belt. If it gets stuck anywhere, you can remove material from there. The back of the logo is not visible, and the other parts will cover up any mess inside. Print out the other parts, and assemble the logo.
Ideally they should fit in with enough strength applied and get stuck there, no glue needed.
Otherwise you need to do some glueing if they fall apart easily, or sand the edges if they can't be pushed together. Done! :) Printing the combined logo If you want to print the whole thing in one piece and paint it afterwards, feel free to download the "combined" version. Warning!
There will be a huge hole inside, which will act as a big bridge, so do this if you:
  • don't want to put in on your belt, or
  • you have a printer with 2 heads and soluble support material.
    • Without the soluble support the inside will be a mess, and you won't be able to push your belt through. It won't be easy to clean up the hole.

Made with Blender, based on the belt as seen in the movie Deadpool.
A big difference is that in the movie it is used as the buckle, so on the sides there is an additional silver part, holding the belt.

There is a musical heart ornament that is just supposed to be printed normally and hung on the tree. Then the two smaller models are light toppers. They just slide over the lights and make it glow in different colors! I printed them in Hatchbox Transparent Red PLA (http://www.amazon.com/HATCHBOX-Transparent-3D-Printer-Filament/dp/B00M0CS68E) so it gives the tree a very nice red glow. It definitely makes it feel more like Valentine's in that room. These were all printed at 0.3mm layer height. The musical heart ornament isn't really affected by changes to layer height or infill, but the transparent parts are heavily affected. So experiment for yourself, but I used 0.3mm layer height and 20% infill to give me a very nice glow around the light. More infill and a smaller layer height will decrease the light that escapes and vice versa. So figure out what you like best!

title: Lightweight Dual to Single Extruder Conversion with Active Cooler for CTC / Flashforge

description.text:
This is a lightweight solution for converting the dual to a single extruder,
supporting the cables from being bent and incorporating a fan and air duct for object cooling. It is recommended to print at least the top part and the nozzle in ABS.
Otherwise the top part tends to warp from motor heat (which is not a problem)
and the nozzle would probably warp too, being close to the extruder and heated bed. All you need to complete the assembly are four 3mm screws, length 15mm to mount
the 40mm (standard or alternative) fan. You can either use self tapping PT screws or
Nylon screws for the ultimate weight saving experience (M3 tapping required).
The other two M3x40mm screws are the original. The nozzle is a snug fit into the body and does not need any glue. All parts are printed upside down! Top part and nozzle are printed with 2 shells, 100% infill.
Body is printed with 2 shells, 15-20% infill.
Support is only recommended for the nozzle where it sits onn the aluminum bar.
No support inside the air ducts needed.

title: Easy Change Split Y-Motor Mount for Prusa i3

description.text:
I am experimenting with a new low-friction Y-carriage using standard ball bearings instead of bushings. As this changes the height of the printing platform, it also requires installing the Y-motor at a different height. Doing this, I found that the usual Prusa i3 Y-motor mounts have two disadvantages: firstly, to replace them you need to completely disassemble the (carefully adjusted!) Y-frame, and, secondly, they are provided only for one vertical height of the motor axis. So this project tries to address both of these shortcomings. These Y-motor mount brackets are split into two halves, so that they can be mounted and unmounted without having to take apart the entire Y-frame. The vertical position of the motor axis with respect to the center of the upper short threaded rod is parametrized, so brackets for any (reasonable) motor height can be generated. Given that the optimal height of the Y-belt depends on the diameter of the pully and the height of the Y-carriage, being able to change the Y-motor bracket without quickly without demounting (and readjusting!) the Y-frame is very useful. The two halves of the bracket have rail cutouts leading from the rod hole to the outside, so that the two half can be slid from two sides around the threaded rods to form a complete and strong motor bracket. In order to make sure that the motor does not give way and always remains perpendicular to the belt, a J-shaped shim is also provided which slips over the threaded rods and keeps the rear end of the motor at the same distance as the front. The SCAD file is fully parametrized, so that it can easily be adapted to just about any Prusa i3 variant: The main parameters of the Y-motor brackets are:
  • diameter of the short threaded rods
  • center-to-center distance between the short threaded rods
  • vertical offset of the motor axis with respect to the upper rod
  • motor outer size and screw hole spacing
  • horizontal offset of the motor from the rod center
